english:
  title: Record of the Pine Wind Pavilion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Yun Jeolgap of the Caoxiist lineage named his dwelling "Pine Wind Pavilion" and asked me to compose a record for it. I said: "The pine possesses an enduring nature—it penetrates through all four seasons and witnesses a thousand years without changing its branches or shedding its leaves. Surely there is a reason for this. The wind as a force rises from eight directions and moves all things, leaving no trace or boundary. Surely there is a reason for this as well.

    Consider this: amid ten thousand peaks and gorges, when one sits deep in such a place, all that the eyes see and ears hear becomes still and bound. Every dust of wandering thought scatters and dissolves. What need has the ravine for the Master? Eyes simply see, ears simply hear. Yet when we hear, does the heart truly move? When we see, does the heart truly move? There must be something that transcends seeing and hearing without being bound by them. Thus appears that blue-green vastness different from common plants, that still purity different from all ordinary sounds.

    To find clarity in daily life and receive its benefit—is this not already enough? Yet the Master has hung a nameplate upon his dwelling and caused people to call it "the Pine Wind Pavilion," saying "I am but a leisured sage of the Pine Wind Pavilion." And whether they follow Buddha's way or not, all alike call it "the Pine Wind Pavilion, where Master Yun dwells." Is this not superfluity piled upon superfluity?

    And yet—when something soars high above, people point and call it Heaven. When something spreads vast below, people point and call it Earth. With a body for movement, with a house for shelter, should one leave no mark, make no sign, would this not be little different from beasts and birds?

    Seekers of the Way visit without end. Those who hear the Master's name will climb cliffs in straw sandals, heedless of treacherous paths, all saying "I come to the Pine Wind Pavilion." Then, sweeping away the nets of doubt and opening the gate to truth, letting fresh breezes of pine wind blow through heart and body alike—the accumulated darkness of countless ages will fade without trace. How then can the benefit it brings to others even be spoken of?

    I have lain ill for long. By fortune I found this Master. Though my understanding remains clouded, how can I say I have gained nothing? So though unbidden, I would have written something to offer—how much more when first asked! Thus, casting aside all shame at my crudeness, I compose this Record of the Pine Wind Pavilion and tell you this: The Pine Wind Pavilion exists throughout the whole earth. Though one dwell ten thousand leagues distant, let it send me a single breath of its cool and pure wind. Otherwise, when shall this fevered mind of mine find solace? I ask you not to forget. Thus ends this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Caoxiist lineage refers to the school of Chan (Zen) Buddhism tracing back to the Sixth Patriarch Huineng of Caoxi.
  - key: ''
    value: This work is written in the style of a Chinese 記 (ji), or commemorative record—a literary form that combines philosophical reflection with biographical tribute.
